        "State what",
        "Suggest a way"
      ]
    },
    {
      "name": "Heat and Temperature Traps",
      "what": "Sometimes forgets that substances still gain heat even when their temperature isn't changing, or mixes up how fast different materials lose heat.",
      "specific_examples": [
        {
          "questionRef": "[8]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "Kaiyangnggg missed that ice is still gaining heat while it melts, even though the temperature stays flat on the graph."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[11]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "He chose glass instead of metal when looking for the container that would cool down the fastest."
        },
        {
          "questionRef": "[36]",
          "type": "mcq",
          "whatWentWrong": "Kaiyangnggg got tricked by the evaporation question, forgetting that a wider surface area leads to more condensation."
        }
      ],
      "strategic_advice": "When you see these heat questions, remember these rules:\n- **Flat lines on a heating graph** → The substance is still **gaining heat** to change state (like melting or boiling)!\n- **Metal containers** → They are **good conductors**, so they lose heat the fastest.\n- **Wider surface area** → More water can evaporate, which leads to more water droplets condensing.",
      "trigger_keywords": [
        "graph",
        "temperature",
        "boiling",
        "melting",
        "evaporated",
        "condensed"
      ]
    },
